In order to mimic the traditional preparation of 
 A. pluriseta herbal medicine, we initially assayed for the general bioactivity of the crude water and methanol extracts. Using a BACTEC MGIT™ 960 system (BD, New York, USA) to assay for antimycobacterial activity, we found that the water crude extract had no antituberculous activity (400 growth unit (GU)), equivalent to GU of the negative control. Interestingly, the methanolic crude extract exhibited high inhibitory activity against MTB similar to SIRE positive control (0 GU; 
 Table 1).
